National Super League side Shabana has suffered a blow after head coach Robert Ojienda resigned on Monday. Ojienda tendered his resignation a day after the team’s 1-0 loss to Kisumu All Stars at Moi Stadium in Kisumu. The tactician did not state why he resigned less than one year into the job. “I take this chance to thank the entire family of Shabana FC for trusting me with the opportunity as the team's head coach since last season," he posted on his Facebook page. "For the time we've been together, I have learnt a lot — which added value to my career as a coach. l leave this great team today a very happy man going by the record that it's better than l found it though the journey was to go beyond their current level (NSL).” He added: “It's with great honour that l thank the management for the enormous support during my tenure in office. Special thanks to my players both from last season and this season. You guys have a special place in my heart, not forgetting members of the technical bench. I wish the team well in their future assignments.” Club chairman Nyandoro Kambi confirmed the coach’s resignation. He said assistant coach Kevin Momanyi and team manager Jared Sani will take charge against Mwatate United at Awendo Stadium on Wednesday. “Momanyi and Sani will be in charge of the team as we look for another coach. We wish the coach all the best in his future endeavours,” Kambi told the Star. Shabana are fourth on the log with 14 points, five behind leaders APS Bomet. At the same time, the club has released six players inclduing Ivorian Frank Ouya, Anthony Ongaga, Ashif Obwaka, Kibet Sang, Mathew Momanyi and Hillary Minishi. Sani added the club has roped in midfielder Ibrahim Ochieng and defender Patrick Ochieng from Kisumu All Stars.